@node intro "JabberBlocky Introduction"

Firstly a big apology for the name of this program, we just couldn't resist! ;-)

JabberBlocky was made after futile attempts to find an IFF to tilemap converter on Aminet (if you know of one @{b}don't@{ub} tell me now!)

If you are wondering what a tilemap is, then this program is almost certainly useless to you and I won't try to explain here.

@endnode


@node install "Installing it"

Nothing to it, just copy the JabberBlocky main file to anywhere you like.

@endnode


@node using "How to use JabberBlocky"

First an explanation of the information diplay:

Current Picture:
The name of the picture you are working on.

Picture Size:
The X/Y size in pixels of the current picture.

Block Count:
The number of unique tiles/total number of tiles in current picture.


Now on to how it's used!
Load your picture to be converted into the program and select the size tiles you would like to make, click on PROCESS and wait (could take a while here), once the processing has been completed, the block count display will be updated to reflect the number of unique tiles found.  You can now click the SAVE button to save the result.


The Save format:

JabberBlocky will save out two files, one is an IFF picture the same size as the input picture but only containing the unique blocks, the other file is a table of 16 bit values pointing to these blocks to enable the reconstruction of the original picture.  It's up to you to write your own reconstruction routine, I can't be doing everything for you!


Problems:   (Maybe you could say BUGS!)

* Uses lots of RAM.
* JabberBlocky will not convert pictures of more than 64 colours.
* Very large pictures (eg. 320x3200) will cause program failure.
* Probably some more, find them yourself!

@endnode


